# Dart Style & Performance Rules

## Code Style
- Use `early returns` to avoid deep nesting — happy path last
- Prefer `final` over `var` for everything that doesn't reassign
- Use `??` and `?.` operators instead of null checks where readable
- No commented-out code — delete it
- No TODO comments in committed code — either do it now or create a task

## Async
- Always use `async/await` — no raw `.then()` chains
- Never `await` inside a `build()` method — use providers or `FutureBuilder`
- `FutureBuilder` only for one-off reads — prefer Riverpod `AsyncNotifier` for anything with state

## Performance
- All list items in `ListView`/`GridView` must use `ListView.builder` — never `ListView(children: [...])`  for dynamic content
- Use `const` widgets aggressively — if a widget has no dynamic data, it must be `const`
- Never call `setState()` from a parent to rebuild a child — extract the child widget instead
- Avoid `Opacity(opacity: 0)` to hide widgets — use `Visibility` or `offstage`

## Typing
- No `dynamic` types — ever
- No implicit `var` on class fields — always typed explicitly
- Nullable types (`String?`) only when null is a genuinely valid state

## Tests
- Every repository method must have a unit test
- Scoring logic in `ScoringConstants` must be fully tested
- Widget tests for at minimum: `McqOptionTile`, `CountdownTimerBar`, `XpProgressBar`
